            <h1 class="display-3 fw-bold mb-4">European Weightlifting Championships 2026: Schedule, stars to watch, and how to follow live</h1>

            <div class="d-flex align-items-center mb-4 text-muted">
                <span class="me-3">By MaxEndLabs Editorial</span>
                <span class="me-3">|</span>
                <span>April 2026</span>
            </div>

            <img src="https://iwf.sport/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/20241210_GSca_SC54556-683x1024.jpg"
                 class="img-fluid rounded-4 shadow-lg mb-5" alt="Guilia Miserendino's Rock Lee style pose">

            <div class="article-content fs-5 lh-lg">
				<div class="starts-to-watch">
		            <p>
			            The <strong>2026 European</strong> Weightlifting <strong>Championships</strong> head to Batumi, Georgia, from 19–26 April, with the 104th edition of the event set to bring together many of Europe’s* leading lifters across eight days of competition.
		            </p>

	                <p>
		                The final entry list is stacked with Olympic medallists, world champions, and established European winners across both programmes, setting up one of the strongest fields of the season.
	                </p>

	                <p>
		                Here's what you need to know ahead of the first lift.
	                </p>

		            <p>
			            <em>
				            *The championships also serve as a qualification event for the Glasgow 2026 Commonwealth Games, which is why guest athletes from Commonwealth nations and territories appear on the start lists, although their performances will not be included in the official European results.
			            </em>
		            </p>
		            <h2>Top athletes to watch at the 2026 European Weightlifting Championships in Batumi</h2>
		            <p>
			            Bulgaria’s <strong>Karlos Nasar</strong> is one of the headline names in Georgia. Entered in the men’s 94kg class, he arrives as the Paris 2024 Olympic champion, the reigning world champion and the 2025 European champion, making him one of the clearest gold-medal favourites in the field. He also holds the current 94kg clean-and-jerk world record at 222kg, set at the 2025&nbsp;IWF World Championships in Førde.
		            </p>

		            <img src="https://img.olympics.com/images/image/private/t_s_16_9_g_auto/t_s_w1460/f_auto/primary/xhrvke7cznqho4wxuzqc"
		                 class="img-fluid rounded-4 shadow-lg mb-5" alt="Karlos Nasar Paris 2024">

		            <p>
			            Nasar isn't the only gold medallist from Paris 2024 competing in Georgia.
		            </p>
		            
		            <p>
			            <strong>Solfrid Koanda</strong> became the first female Norwegian weightlifter to become an Olympic champion after triumphing in the 81kg class two years ago. The 27-year-old followed that milestone with a second world title in 2025 (in the 86kg class), and is chasing a fifth&nbsp;<em>consecutive</em> European title.&nbsp;
		            </p>

		            <img src="https://ewf.sport/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/Photo-Geir-Owe-Fredheim-Team-Norway-2.jpg"
		                 class="img-fluid rounded-4 shadow-lg mb-5" alt="Solfrid Koanda Paris 2024">

		            <p>
			            Great Britain’s challenge is led by <strong>Emily Campbell</strong> in the women’s +86kg class, where the defending European champion returns as a two-time Olympic medallist, having won silver at Tokyo 2020 and bronze at Paris 2024. <strong>Sarah Davies</strong> also adds to the British contingent, stepping into the 63kg class as the reigning European champion after winning last year’s title at 64kg.
		            </p>

					<img src="https://i.pinimg.com/736x/4a/db/84/4adb8451c93f9382ecf5ef5108fdfdf8.jpg"
						 class="img-fluid rounded-4 shadow-lg mb-5" alt="Emily Campbell and Sarah Davies Batumi 2019">
					
		            <p>
			            Romania’s <strong>Mihaela Cambei</strong> is a leading name at 53kg after taking Olympic silver at Paris 2024.
		            </p>

					<img src="https://barbend.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Untitled-design-2024-08-07T194352.408.jpg"
						 class="img-fluid rounded-4 shadow-lg mb-5" alt="Mihaela Cambei training session">

		            <p>
			            Armenia also bring major pedigree into the men’s events. <strong>Varazdat Lalayan</strong> enters the +110kg class as the returning European champion, Paris 2024 Olympic silver medallist and reigning world champion, while <strong>Simon Martirosyan</strong> enters the 110kg category as a two-time Olympic silver medallist.
		            </p>

		            <img src="https://i.pinimg.com/736x/d4/7e/00/d47e0088c7b5b0dd98fd4ab6ab5246db.jpg"
		                 class="img-fluid rounded-4 shadow-lg mb-5" alt="Varazdat Lalayan and Simon Martirosyan">
				</div>
	            <div class="schedule">
